						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">I think the exact opposite. 3D is very useful for creating fluid sprite animations, but at bigger sizes, 3D just doesn't have the charm of hand-drawn art.</div><br />As long as the artist can touch up the renders by hand, I think starting with a 3D base is a great way to go. Everything stays in proportion and it is easier to animate things fluidly. Not sure why bigger sizes wouldn't look good. Any examples? <br /><br />This game used 3D models as the starting point for hand-drawn sprite animations:  <a href="http://www.siliconera.com/2012/02/09/the-art-of-blazblue-part-2-animation-phase/" class="postlink">http://www.siliconera.com/2012/02/09/the-art-of-blazblue-part-2-animation-phase/</a><br /><br />And this Game Boy Color game seems to use sprites converted from 3D models: <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3ge6OVwttlA" class="postlink">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3ge6OVwttlA</a><br />If that style was applied to a NES game it would look very unique and modern.</div>

